Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by Yumeng¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

In this project, I will explore the Ford GoBike System Data of year 2018.This dataset includes information about each trip in a bike-sharing system in greater San Francisco Bay area.

# read all csv file into one DataFrame
df_orig = pd.DataFrame()
csv_list = []
for i in glob.glob('*.csv'):
    df_single = pd.read_csv(i)
    csv_list.append(df_single)
df_orig = pd.concat(csv_list, ignore_index=True)

There are a few quality issues need to be cleaned:

  • 'start_time' and 'end_time' datatype is string but not datetime
  • 'bike_id' datatype is integer but not string
  • 'member_birth_year' datatype is float but not integer. This is caused by "NaN can't be stored in an integer array". We will not fix this issue then
  • 'start_station_id', 'start_station_name' , 'end_station_id', 'end_station_name' information is not very helpful for this project. Those columns can be removed
  • Missing values in columns 'member_birth_year', 'member_gender'
  • 'member_gender' column has 'Other' value

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are $1396765$ trips information in this dataset. There are 12 variables / columns. From the dataset we have the following information about each trip:

  • Trip duration, start and end time
  • Trip start and end location
  • Bike information
  • User information

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in investigating the relationship of 'duration_sec' with the other features. I am also interested in the number of trips during different time frame.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I would expect that subscribed users ride duration is longer than subscribed users. It is also likely that ride duration varies among different age groups and genders.
The time of the day, day of the week, month of the year may also have effects on ride duration and number of trips.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The variable duration_sec has many outliers. I took a look at the interquartile range and truncate the outliers. I also create a new column duration_min to convert the duration from seconds to minutes for easy understanding purpose. Since the distribution is right skewed, I used log transformation.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I created the variable age. I noticed that age variable has some inaccurate data and I cleaned the dataset.

To investigate the trips time in different time frame, I used variable start_time to create 3 more variables time_day, weekday and month.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The feature of interest, duration, is correlated to user type. The subscribers trip duration is in general less than customers.
The most common trip duration is in 5 10 minutes. Within this range, the users are mainly 28 33 years old.
The duration does not seem to be correlated to variables time of day, day of week, or month of year.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

We took a look at the relationship between user type and age. For both user type, the majority of the users are around 30 years old.

However, the distribution of variable time of day, day of week are quite different in those 2 user type groups. For subscriber group, the distributions of time of day and day of week variables are also the same as the distribution we saw in univariate exploration. For customer group, the distributions of time of day and day of week variables are almost uniform, which does not depend on different time

For customer group, the most frequent trip duration is 5-15 minutes; the distribution is also not as narrow as the subscriber group. Most of the users are between 28-33 years old, which is the same as the subscriber group.

The plot shows that from 9am to 11pm, the trip duration mean of the weekends is higher than workdays. But this trend is noisy from 0am to 8am. Interestingly, at around 5am, the trip duration mean of weekends is much higher than workdays.
We also overserve an increasing trip duration mean trend from 9am to 3pm, then a decreasing trend from 4pm to 11pm.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

During the bivariate exploration, we didnt see a big variation of trip duration mean at different time of the day. There doesnt seem to be a strong correlation between time and trip duration mean. However, when we categorized by user type, we can see that trip duration mean varies in Customer group. There is an obvious increasing trend from 5am to 3pm, and decreasing trend from 4pm to 11pm.
Also, the trip duration has a correlation with different time of the day especially during weekends.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Looking back on faceting heatmap plots, there is no systematic interaction between time of day and age. But we can see that elder people are not likely to take a trip during early time of the day.
From the line plot, there seems to be an interation between time of the day and days of week (workdays vs weekends).
